teams.strDescriptionEN:
Beijing Great Wall is a Chinese professional women's basketball club based in Beijing, playing in the Women's Chinese Basketball Association (WCBA). The team is owned by Beijing Shougang Co., Ltd., which also owns the Beijing Ducks men's basketball team. Beijing Great Wall sometimes also carries the name of its sponsor BBMG.

The team won 4 WCBA championships, first in 2012 and more recently from 2016 to 2018.

Heilongjiang Dragons (Chinese: 华龙女篮; pinyin: Huálóng Nǚlán) is a Chinese professional women's basketball club based in Daqing, Heilongjiang, playing in the Women's Chinese Basketball Association (WCBA).

Created by Jiang Zuozhi in the 1990s, it is the oldest Women's Basketball team in China.

The club has formed several important players, including Miao Lijie, Ma Zongqing, Liu Yutong, and others.

Guangdong Vermilion Birds is a Chinese professional women's basketball club based in Dongguan, Guangdong, playing in the Women's Chinese Basketball Association (WCBA). It was known as Guangdong Dolphins from 2007–2018 and Guangdong Kapok before 2007.

The Vermilion Bird is a mythical creature in Chinese culture.
Hebei Win Power is a Chinese professional women's basketball club in the Women's Chinese Basketball Association (WCBA), based in Hengshui, Hebei.
Heilongjiang Dragons (华龙女篮) is a Chinese professional women's basketball club based in Daqing, Heilongjiang, playing in the Women's Chinese Basketball Association (WCBA).

Henan Phoenix is a Chinese professional women's basketball club based in Henan, playing in the Women's Chinese Basketball Association (WCBA). Before 2014 it was known as Henan Elephants. The team is sometimes known by the name of its sponsor Yichuan Rural Commercial Bank (a bank based in Yichuan County, Henan).
Jiangsu Phoenix is a Chinese professional women's basketball club based in Jiangsu, playing in the Women's Chinese Basketball Association (WCBA).

Liaoning Zhongda Aluminium Flying Eagles (simplified Chinese: 辽宁忠大铝业飞鹰; traditional Chinese: 遼寧忠大鋁業飛鷹; pinyin: liáo níng zhōng dà lǚ yè fēi yīng) is a Chinese professional women's basketball club in Liaoning, playing in the Women's Chinese Basketball Association (WCBA). Liaoning Zhongda Aluminum Co. has been the team's corporate sponsor since 2015.

From 2005 to 2015, the team was known as Liaoning Hengye Golden Leopards and sponsored by Liaoning Hengye Group. Before 2005 it was known as Liaoning Big Dipper (辽宁北斗星女篮).

The Shaanxi Tianze Red Wolves are a Chinese professional women's basketball club based in Weinan, Shaanxi, playing in the Women's Chinese Basketball Association (WCBA). The team is owned by the Tianze Group.

teams.strStadium: Baoshan Sports Centre / Baosteel Sports Centre
teams.strDescriptionEN: Shanghai Baoshan Dahua Swordfish is a Chinese professional women's basketball club based in Shanghai, playing in the Women's Chinese Basketball Association (WCBA). It is co-owned by Baoshan District government, Shanghai Sports Institute, and Dahua Group. Before 2014 it was known as Shanghai Octopus, affiliated with the Shanghai Media Group. Between 2007 and 2008 it was sponsored by the Xiyang Group.

Shanxi Xing Rui Flame is a professional women's basketball club located in Taiyuan, Shanxi, China, playing in the Women's Chinese Basketball Association (WCBA). It is also known by its sponsor's name Zhuyeqing. Led by WNBA star Maya Moore, the club won 3 consecutive WCBA championships from 2013 to 2015.

The Xiamen Women's basketball team is a highly skilled and competitive team based in Xiamen, China. Comprised of talented and dedicated female athletes, this team has established itself as a force to be reckoned with in the world of basketball.

Known for their exceptional teamwork and strategic play, the Xiamen Women's team consistently displays a high level of skill and determination on the court. Their players possess a strong basketball IQ and are adept at executing both offensive and defensive plays.

The team's roster is filled with versatile and dynamic players who excel in various positions. From agile guards who can drive to the basket and shoot from long range, to powerful forwards who dominate the paint and grab rebounds, the Xiamen Women's team boasts a well-rounded lineup.

Coached by experienced and knowledgeable mentors, the team is constantly refining their skills and tactics to stay ahead of the competition. Their commitment to continuous improvement is evident in their disciplined training sessions and meticulous game preparation.

Off the court, the Xiamen Women's team is known for their sportsmanship and dedication to their community. They actively engage in charitable initiatives and youth development programs, inspiring the next generation of basketball players.

With a strong fan base and a reputation for excellence, the Xiamen Women's basketball team is a source of pride for the city of Xiamen. Their electrifying performances and unwavering determination make them a formidable opponent in any competition they participate in.

Xinjiang Tian Shan Magic Deer is a Chinese professional women's basketball club based in Ürümqi, Xinjiang, playing in the Women's Chinese Basketball Association (WCBA). The team also plays some home games in Changji.

The nickname Tian Shan magic deer is derived from Tian Shan wapiti, an elk subspecies native to Tian Shan in Xinjiang.
